# Auth provider per service family (awaits ADR-01)

## Rule
Until ADR-01 resolves, each service keeps its current auth provider; no service switches without an ADR decision. Providers per family (from `building-block-to-services.json`):

- **fy-iam-go (JWT RS256)**: fb-rates-go, fb-iqs, quote-ai-backend, quote-ai-frontend, skipper, skipperroutes, freightify-web, fb-shipper-frontend.
- **Keycloak OIDC**: admin-backend, admin-frontend.
- **Google OAuth (`@freightify.com`)**: extraction-frontend.
- **API key**: extraction-service, rate-agent, qa-agent, rate-extraction-service.
- **None**: fb-documents (custom element, host owns auth).

## Why
The split is load-bearing: fb-rates-go / fb-iqs tenant middleware is coupled to fy-iam-go's `vendorId` claim; admin-backend's permission model is coupled to Keycloak realm roles; extraction-frontend's `@freightify.com` restriction is a simple internal-only gate. Changing provider per-service without consolidation produces token-translation bugs.

## Constraints
- A new service must pick an existing provider from this list (matching the family it joins).
- Cross-family calls propagate the caller's token only when the callee accepts it; otherwise use the callee's API-key slot.
- Any proposal to change a service's provider must land as an ADR-01 amendment before the code change.
- Frontend apps never talk to two providers from the same code path; dual-token flows (quote-ai-frontend → quote-ai-backend and Skipper) use separate HTTP clients per provider.

## Examples

### Good
> New IQS-adjacent backend service: adopt fy-iam-go JWT to inherit the `vendorId` tenant middleware chain.

### Bad
> New admin tool bolts Google OAuth onto admin-backend because "it's simpler" — fractures ADR-01 further.

